{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
In [[medicine]], '''atony''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|,|t|oʊ|.|n|i}}; also ''atonia'') is a condition in which a [[muscle]] has lost its strength. It is frequently associated with the conditions [[atonic seizure]], [[atonic colon]], [[uterine atony]], [[gastrointestinal atony]] (occurs postoperatively) and [[choreatic atonia]].
Atony can also refer to the paralyzed or extremely relaxed state of skeletal muscles in [[rapid eye movement sleep]] (REM sleep) in most warm-blooded animals.
The term ''atony'' comes from the [[Ancient Greek]] ἀτονία (''atonia''), "slackness, debility".
==See also== * [[Hypotonia]] * [[Muscle weakness]]
