'''Axel Perneczky''' (1 November 1945 – 24 January 2009) was a renowned [[Hungary|Hungarian]] [[neurosurgery|neurosurgeon]], who for the majority of his career, practised neurosurgery in [[Mainz]] in [[Germany]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} He was a major contributor to the development of [[endoscopy|endoscopic]] and minimally invasive neurosurgical procedures,<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Doglietto F, Prevedello DM, Jane JA, Han J, Laws ER |title=Brief history of endoscopic transsphenoidal surgery--from Philipp Bozzini to the First World Congress of Endoscopic Skull Base Surgery |journal=Neurosurg Focus |volume=19 |issue=6 |pages=E3 |year=2005 |pmid=16398480 |doi= }}</ref> particularly in the field of cerebrovascular neurosurgery.
Dr. Perneckzky was the editor of the journal Minimally Invasive Neurosurgery, published by [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]].
