;1977
* Dr. Donna Mildvan, chief of Infectious Disease at [[Mount Sinai Beth Israel|Beth Israel Hospital]] and colleague Dr. [[Dan William]] draw a connection between symptoms seen in gay male patients<ref name=JAMA-VenerealTransmissionMaleHomosexuals-1977>{{cite journal|last1=Mildvan, MD|first1=Donna|last2=Gelb, MD|first2=Alvin M.|last3=William, MD|first3=Daniel|title=Venereal Transmission of Enteric Pathogens in Male Homosexuals: Two Case Reports|journal=[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]|date=26 September 1977|volume=238|issue=13|pages=1387–1389|doi=10.1001/jama.1977.03280140065022}}</ref>

*The first evidence for HIV-1 infection among IV drug users in New York City is from three cases of AIDS in children born in 1977.<ref name=Jarlais_1>{{cite journal| title=HIV-1 Infection Among Intravenous Drug Users in Manhattan, New York City, From 1977 Through 1987| author1=D.C. Des Jarlais| author2=S.R. Friedman| author3=D.M. Novick| author4=J.L. Sotheran| author5=P. Thomas| author6=S.R. Yancovitz| author7=D. Mildvan| author8=J. Weber| author9=M.J. Kreek| author10=R. Maslansky| author11=S. Bartelme| author12=T. Spira |author13=M. Marmor| journal=The Journal of the American Medical Association| date=17 February 1989| volume=261| issue=7| pages=1008-1012| doi=10.1001/jama.1989.03420070058030}}</ref> This likely mother-to-child transmission within Manhattan "strongly suggests that the introduction of HIV-1 into the IV drug-use group occurred around 1975 or 1976, or perhaps even earlier."<ref name=Jarlais_1/><ref name=Friedman_1>{{cite journal| title=Harm reduction theory: Users culture, micro-social indigenous harm reduction, and the self-organization and outside-organizing of users’ groups| author1=S.R. Friedman| author2=W. de Jong| author3=D. Rossi| author4=G. Touzé| author5=R. Rockwell| author6=D.C.D. Jarlais| author7=R. Elovich| journal=The International Journal on Drug Policy| date=28 December 2006| volume=18| issue=2| pages=107-117| doi=10.1016/j.drugpo.2006.11.006}}</ref>

;1979
* Dr. Donna Mildvan identifies reports of a virulent diarrhea that is called Gay Bowel Syndrome<ref name=AIDS-Doctors-2002>{{cite book|last1=Bayer|first1=Ronald|last2=Oppenheimer|first2=Gerald M.|title=AIDS Doctors: Voices from the Epidemic|date=2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-515239-5|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/aids-doctors-voices-from-the-epidemic/oclc/52472788/viewport|oclc=255446043}}</ref>{{rp|13}}

;1981
* New York City Infectious Diseases Intercity Rounds records first cases of gay-related immunodeficiency diseases<ref name=NYMag-FightingAIDS-1987>{{cite news|last1=Hopkins Tanne|first1=Janice|title=Fighting AIDS: On the front lines against the plague|url=http://nymag.com/health/features/49240/|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=12 January 1987}}</ref>{{rp|9}} Dr. [[Lawrence D. Mass]] publishes a report in the newspaper, ''[[New York Native]],'' about the spread of a mysterious disease, and warning gay men that the disease was being spread as a result of having frequent sex with other men.<ref name=NYNative-GayCancer-1981>{{cite news|last1=Mass|first1=Lawrence|title=Cancer in the gay community|url=|work=[[New York Native]]|date=27 July 1981}}</ref> Kaposi's sarcoma is thought to be the main problem
* Dr. Lawrence Mass, Larry Kramer and others form the [[Gay Men's Health Crisis|Gay Men's Health Crisis (GMHC)]], the first New York City nonprofit devoted to provide services to people with AIDS

;1982
* February: Health Commissioner [[David Sencer]] listed increasing rate of Kaposi's sarcoma fourth in the city's health department priority list
* February: When asked by a reporter for the ''New York Native'' if news of the epidemic would be communicated via mass media, Sencer declines<ref name=AmericanScholar-OrdinarinessAIDS-2006>{{cite news|last1=Alcabes|first1=Philip|title=The Ordinariness of AIDS: Can a disease that tells us so much about ourselves ever be anything but extraordinary?|url=https://theamericanscholar.org/the-ordinariness-of-aids/#.V3gRuZMrLXG|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[The American Scholar]]|date=1 June 2006}}</ref>
* Findings in a report by Sencer and U.S. Center for Disease Control show that over half the 225 cases in Kaposi's sarcoma in the United States by January 1982 happened in New York
* The Center for Disease Control gives AIDS (Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome) its name<ref name=MMWR-AIDS-CDC-2011>{{cite journal|last1=Curran, MD|first1=James W.|last2=Jaffe, MD|first2=Harold W.|title=AIDS: The Early Years and CDC's Response|journal=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (MMWR)]]|date=7 October 2011|volume=60|issue=4|pages=64–69|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention}}</ref>
* GMHC holds the first benefit to collect funds for the epidemic<ref name=NYMag-GayPlague-1982>{{cite news|last1=VerMeulen|first1=Michael|title=The Gay Plague: A mysterious immune disorder is spreading like wildfire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4-cCAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA3&dq=new%20york%20magazine%20and%20michael%20vermeulen%20and%20%22gay%20plague%22&pg=PA52#v=onepage&q=new%20york%20magazine%20and%20michael%20vermeulen%20and%20%22gay%20plague%22&f=false|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=31 May 1982|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|62}}
* Rodger MacFarlane, president of GMHC, begins an AIDS hotline in his own apartment
* GMHC co-founder Larry Kramer became a public spokesperson known for comments made to the press, including sharp criticisms of Ed Koch and David Sencer for their lack of action
* Dr. Michael Lange was of one the first to outline the disaster that lay ahead.<ref name=NYNative-HIVDebate-1988>{{cite news|last1=Lauritsen|first1=John|title=The HIV Debate|url=http://www.virusmyth.com/aids/hiv/jldebate.htm|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[New York Native]]|date=22 February 1988}}</ref>
* David Sencer tells Lawrence Mass that gay health would soon be his top priority but insisted on keeping the focus on preventative medicine; did not consider Kaposi's sarcoma important enough to ask for additional funds. Sencer changes his mind on the importance of Kaposi's sarcoma after attending first citywide meeting of Kaposi's sarcoma researchers
* New York City mayor Ed Koch declines to meet with activists<ref name=NYMag-EdKoch-AIDSCrisis-Failure-2013>{{cite news|last1=France|first1=David|title=Ed Koch and the AIDS Crisis: His Greatest Failure|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/02/koch-and-the-aids-crisis-his-greatest-failure.html|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2 February 2013}}</ref>
* Congress allocated US$2.6 million for CDC AIDS research but the Reagan administration opposed these measures<ref name=EncylopediaOfAIDS-2014>{{cite book|last1=Curran|first1=James W.|last2=Piot|first2=Peter|editor1-last=Smith|editor1-first=Raymond A.|editor2-last=Rosett|editor2-first=Jane|title=Encyclopedia of AIDS: A Social, Political, Cultural, and Scientific Record of the HIV Epidemic|date=2014|publisher=Routledge|location=Oxfordshire, England|isbn=978-0-203-30549-2|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10981147|accessdate=2 July 2016|oclc=899008229}}</ref>{{rp|204}}

;1983
* New York City virologists [[Mathilde Krim]] and [[Joseph Sonnabend]] found the AIDS Medical Foundation (AMF). It  later becomes the [[amfAR, The Foundation for AIDS Research|American Foundation for AIDS Research]] (amfAR), and is still active today
* Larry Kramer writes the article "1,112 and counting" for the ''[[New York Native]],'' where he viciously attacks Mayor Koch and city's health department for being ineffective<ref name="NYNative-Kramer-1112andCounting-1983">{{cite news|last1=Kramer|first1=Larry|title=1,112 and Counting|url=http://bilerico.lgbtqnation.com/2011/06/larry_kramers_historic_essay_aids_at_30.php|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[New York Native]]|issue=59|date=14 March 1983}}</ref>
* Mayor Koch and David Sencer announce the formation of an office for Gay and Lesbian Health Concern under director Roger Enlow<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|309}}
* Representatives [[Ted Weiss]] from New York and [[Henry Waxman]] from Los Angeles led congressional investigations into the Reagan administration's AIDS-related policy efforts<ref name=EncylopediaOfAIDS-2014 />
* April 18: Larry Kramer resigns from the GMHC board<ref name=Shilts-AndtheBandPlayedOn />{{rp|275}}
* April 30: The GMHC sponsors the first major fundraising event for AIDS, a benefit performance of a benefit performance of the Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus at Madison Square Garden. The program listed an official proclamation of "Aid AIDS Week" from Mayor Koch<ref name=Shilts-AndtheBandPlayedOn />{{rp|282}} On October 1, GMHC sponsors "The World's Toughest Rodeo" benefit at Madison Square Garden<ref name=GMHC-WorldsToughestRodeo-1983>{{cite web|title=Gay Men's Health Crisis Inc. presents the World's Toughest Rodeo|url=http://aep.lib.rochester.edu/node/45537|website=[[Gay Men's Health Crisis|Gay Men's Health Crisis (GMHC)]]|publisher=[[University of Rochester]]|accessdate=2 July 2016|date=1983}}</ref><ref>http://aep.lib.rochester.edu/node/45537</ref>
* June: Mayor Koch joins San Francisco mayor Dianne Feinstein, Washington mayor Marion Barry, and New Orleans mayor Ernest Morial to push a resolution through the U.S. Conference of Mayors calling for "government assurance of adequate medical, hospital, and hospice care for victims of AIDS" as well as more funding for medical research. The four big-city mayors fight off opposition from three cabinet members dispatched by the Reagan administration to oppose the resolution and declare AIDS a local responsibility<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|310}}
* New York University holds a three-day conference on AIDS where Dr. Joseph Bove argues against the evidence of blood transmission<ref name=Shilts-AndtheBandPlayedOn />{{rp|249}}
* Dr. Kevin Cahill organizes a conference at Lenox Hill Hospital with the intent to "attracts all the big-name AIDS researchers who could deliver state-of-the-art information on the epidemic." Cahill also arranged for immediate publication of their findings to initiate first Senate hearing on the syndrome<ref name=Shilts-AndtheBandPlayedOn />{{rp|265–266}}
* Media coverage on AIDS begins to boom: outlets like ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine<ref name=Newsweek-30YearsAgoAIDS-2014>{{cite news|last1=Fader|first1=Lainna|title=Newsweek Rewind: 30 Years Ago, Scientists Discovered the Cause of AIDS|url=http://www.newsweek.com/newsweek-rewind-30-years-ago-scientists-discovered-cause-hiv-248566|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=24 April 2014}}</ref> and other major newspapers nationwide publish over 650 stories between December and April. Coverage included shortfalls of resources for AIDS research and education in NYC, and how the response in San Francisco was more effective<ref name=NYTimes-SFranCombatsFear-1983>{{cite news|title=San Francisco Seeks to Combat Fear of AIDS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/05/22/us/san-francisco-seeks-to-combat-fear-of-aids.html|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 May 1983}}</ref> 
* Dr. Mathilde Krim plans to meet with New York City officials (Carol Bellamy, who did not see her, and Andrew Stein) to discuss a proposal for a coordinated city response based on San Francisco programs. Krim described the attitude as ineffectual: "nobody gave a damn"<ref name=Shilts-AndtheBandPlayedOn />{{rp|380}}
* Larry Kramer writes a play called ''[[The Normal Heart]]'', which dramatizes the beginning of the AIDS epidemic, "satirizing Koch and (Herb) Richman as callous bureaucrats"<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|310–311}}
* The "Denver Principles" are drafted at a conference convened by [[People With AIDS]] (PWA)-New York and [[People With AIDS]] (PWA)-San Francisco laying the groundwork for underground AIDS activism. This manifesto rejected the paternalism of the professional medical establishment and calls for participation in decision making at all levels<ref name=HistoryPWASelfEmpowerment-1988>{{cite journal|last1=Callen|first1=Michael|last2=Turner|first2=Dan|title=A History of the PWA Self-Empowerment Movement|journal=Lesbian & Gay Health Education Foundation Program Booklet|date=1988|url=http://michaelcallen.com/mikes-writing/a-history-of-the-pwa-self-empowerment-movement/}}</ref>
* Decision in the trial The People v. West 12 Street Tenants Corporation in favor of Dr. Joseph Sonnabend due to discrimination. New York becomes known as the nation's center for aggressive civil liberties litigation on behalf of people with AIDS and their circles<ref name="LambdaLegal-PositiveHistory-2011">{{cite news|last1=Chew|first1=Saly|title=Positive History|url=https://www.lambdalegal.org/sites/default/files/publications/downloads/impact_201102_positive-history.pdf|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[Lambda Legal|Lambda Legal Impact]]|date=Winter 2011|pages=10–12}}</ref>{{rp|11}}
* Advocates for AIDS research in 14th Annual Lesbian and Gay Pride Parade attack sensationalist approaches from the press, asking for research, not for hysteria<ref>Ashton?</ref>
* NYC accounts for more than half of AIDS deaths and new infections in the country
* New York State establishes an AIDS Advisory Council<ref name=NYSDOH-AIDSAdvisoryCouncil>{{cite web|title=New York State AIDS Advisory Council|url=http://www.health.ny.gov/diseases/aids/providers/workgroups/aac/|website=New York State Department of Health|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>
* Koch meets with the AIDS Network to discuss efforts to mobilize agencies to fight AIDS. Koch allows for the selling of a city-owned building, formerly the Food Trades Vocational High School at 208 West 13th Street to AIDS organizations on "favorable terms."<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|310}} This site becomes the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Community Center<ref name=NYTimes-LGBTCenterHistory-2008>{{cite news|last1=Dunlap|first1=David W.|title=A 25-Year-Old Gay Landmark, Built Before the Civil War|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/07/08/a-25-year-old-gay-landmark-built-before-the-civil-war/|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=8 July 2008}}</ref>
* August: Secretary Margaret Heckler announces her support for transferring $40 million in federal funds to AIDS research. In her announcement, she is accompanied by Koch since in 1983 New York City was the site of 42% of reported AIDS cases<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|310}}

;1984
* Mayor Koch runs for reelection
* GMHC publishes a safer sex booklet, "Healthy Sex is Great Sex"<ref name=NYTimes-AIDS-Education-1985>{{cite news|last1=Gross|first1=Jane|title=Homosexuals Stepping Up AIDS Education|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/09/22/nyregion/homosexuals-stepping-up-aids-education.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 September 1985}}</ref>
* The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control]] asks GMHC to assist them in creating public conferences on AIDS<ref name=NYPL-GMHC-Collection>{{cite web|title=Gay Men's Health Crisis records. 1975–1978, 1982–1999 [bulk 1982–1993]|url=http://archives.nypl.org/mss/1126|website=[[New York Public Library]], Archives & Manuscripts|accessdate=2 July 2016|format=Finding Aid}}</ref> 
* November: [[Ronald Reagan]] is re-elected as president. AIDS was not addressed in the campaign<ref name="MotherJones-Shilts-InColdBlood-1987">{{cite news|last1=Shilts|first1=Randy|title=In Cold Blood: Why The Reagan Administration Ignored Its Own Medical Advisors on AIDS|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SucDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT7&dq=Mother+Jones.+Randy+Shilts.+In+cold+blood.&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitqJD8ydXNAhXH5YMKHW5dCM8Q6AEIHjAA#v=onepage&q=Randy%20Shilts%20Finally%2C%20something%20interesting&f=false|accessdate=2 July 2016|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|date=November 1987|language=en|pages=25–33; 44–47}}</ref>{{rp|32}}

;1985
* Koch wins a third term. After the election, Koch and Governor Cuomo work to close the gay bathhouses<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|313}}
* April: The First International AIDS Conference, organized by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, is held in Atlanta, Georgia<ref name=EncylopediaOfAIDS-2014 /><ref name=AIDS-HistoryIntlAIDSConferences-2012>{{cite web|title=A History of the International AIDS Conferences|url=http://www.aids2012.org/WebContent/File/History%20of%20the%20IAC.pdf|website=AIDS 2012|accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>
* Dr. Mildvan recorded hearing an estimate that one million people in the world at that time might be harboring the HIV retrovirus<ref name=NYTimes-AIDS-Data-1985>{{cite news|last1=Altman|first1=Lawrence K., M.D.|title=The Doctor's World: AIDS Data Pour in as Studies Proliferate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/23/science/the-doctor-s-world-aids-data-pour-in-as-studies-proliferate.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 April 1985}}</ref>
* April: Kramer's play ''[[The Normal Heart]]'' opens at Joseph Papp's Public Theater, starring D.W. Moffett, Phillip Richard Allen, Brad Davis and Concetta Tomei<ref name=NYTimes-NormalHeart-Review-1985>{{cite news|last1=Rich|first1=Frank|title=Theater: 'The Normal Heart,' by Larry Kramer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/22/theater/theater-the-normal-heart-by-larry-kramer.html|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 April 1985}}</ref> It is nominated for a Tony award and wins one for a revival in 2011
* As a result of the play, Koch responded by claiming that the city was spending US$31 million a year on AIDS (most of that money paid for care for AIDS patients in city hospitals and did not represent new spending), and he announced a US$6 million increase in city AIDS funding, with new programs for subsidized housing, home care, added resources for acute at hospitals, better coordination of medical teams, and educational program, hospice care, and more research funding.<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|311}}
* June 15: GMHC and New York [[Physicians for Human Rights]] sponsor an AIDS Conference at [[Hunter College]]
* July 22: 4,133 cases of AIDS have been reported in New York City, an increase of 207 cases from the previous month
* October 2: Hollywood film actor Rock Hudson was one of the first celebrities to publicly acknowledge that he had AIDS. His death and struggle to receive treatment brought attention to the problems faced by PWAs<ref name=NYTimes-RockHudson-Obit-1985>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=Joseph|title=Rock Hudson, Screen Idol, Dies at 59|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/10/03/arts/rock-hudson-screen-idol-dies-at-59.html|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 October 1985}}</ref>
* No longer trusting Sencer, Koch names Victor Botnick co-chair of the AIDS Policy and Planning Committee<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|311}}
* Based on the findings of a medical panel, Koch supports the enrollment of children with HIV in New York City public schools<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|312}}

;1986
* Gay rights bill that had been introduced six times by Major Edward Koch since 1978 is passed by the Council in 1986
* GMHC holds the first AIDS Walk in New York City. Over 4.500 people participate and raise US$710,000<ref name=GMHC-HIV-AIDS-Timeline />
* October: GMHC's client base expanded to include heterosexual men and women, hemophiliacs, intravenous drug-users, and children<ref name=NYPL-GMHC-Collection />{{rp|ix}}

;1987
* Activists assemble to form [[ACT UP|ACT UP (AIDS Coalition To Unleash Power)]]. The group's first action was a march on Wall Street protesting the costs and lack of availability of HIV treatment drugs<ref name=ACTUPNY-Chronology-2014>{{cite web|title=25 Yr Chronology: ACT UP Accomplishments and Partial Chronology|url=http://actupny.com/actions/index.php/the-community|website=[[ACT UP|ACT UP New York]]|accessdate=2 July 2016|date=31 December 2014}}</ref> 
* The New York State Department of Health publishes a survey of maternal infection that indicates that 1 of every 61 women giving birth is infected with AIDS compared to one out of 749 in the rest of the state; prevailing in areas of poverty and minority residents (higher in the Bronx than on  Staten Island)<ref name=EncylopediaOfNYC-2010 />{{rp|16}}

;1988
* New York City's healthcare and social welfare systems are becoming increasingly overwhelmed; 13 percent of the inpatient beds in facilities maintained by the Health and Hospitals Corporation are occupied by AIDS patients<ref name=EncylopediaOfNYC-2010 />{{rp|16}}
* November: Koch supports the start of a needle exchange program<ref name=Soffer-EdKochReuildingNYC-2010 />{{rp|313}}

;1989
* Over 2,000 New York City women through 1989 are labeled as being infected because of their own intravenous drug use. This number is over two and a half times higher that the women considered to have been infected by sex with a man at risk
* Towards the end of the 1980s, AIDS became the leading cause of death in New York City for men between the ages of 25 to 44 and [[Black Women’s Health Imperative|black women]] between the ages of 15 to 44 years<ref name=EncylopediaOfNYC-2010 />{{rp|16}}<ref name=NYTimes-LeadingKiller-1995>{{cite news|last1=Altman|first1=Lawrence K.|title=AIDS Is Now the Leading Killer of Americans From 25 to 44|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/01/31/science/aids-is-now-the-leading-killer-of-americans-from-25-to-44.html|accessdate=1 July 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=31 January 1995}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Dirty 30|title=EP 101 - DIRTY 30 "Black Women & Single Motherhood" - Documentary Series on HIV and AIDS|date=2014-11-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lGcisAjhswQ|accessdate=2016-07-26}}</ref>

